text.tspan: User makes HTTP request
User clicks link or types in URL into their
browser and makes a HTTP request to
the server.
Server loads frontend page
The webserver runs the frontend PHP file
from the filesystem which sets up the application
and specifies a controller and action.
IoC container gets controller
The IoC container instantiates the controller
by calling its constructor with all the
dependencies it needs.
Pre filters executed
The pre-response filters are executed. These
do things like ensure the user is logged in, check
security information etc.
Controller action called
The controller action function is called and
required data (e.g. URL parameters) are supplied
to the function. The controller calls other classes to
retrieve data from the database, process data etc.
View is prepared
The controller tells the application to render a
view. The application gathers data from the controller
and adds in any global view variables.
Terminology
IoC container:
This simply stores objects and then lets
you get them back out. It knows some
classes implement interfaces and will
return the respective classes when you
ask it to look up an interface. It will also
create class instances for you,
resolving the constructor parameters.
Controller:
A class which handles a set of related
web requests.
Action:
A function on a controller which deals
with one type of request.
Flash session:
A session that lasts for one request
before it is deleted. Good for storing
temporary data.
Filter:
Code that runs either before or after
every action. Useful for avoiding
duplicating code such as checking to
ensure the user is logged in.
Post filters executed
The post-response filters are executed. These
do things to the respone after it has been made,
e.g. adding headers common to every response.
Final response sent to user
The final response and any headers are sent to
the user and the browser renders it.
Justification
• Data logic and view logic are
kept separate, code is easier to
maintain
• Interfaces used throughout allows
alternative implementations to be
swapped in in one place only - e.g.
changing from SQLite to MySQL
• Easy compliance with SOLID OOP
design principles
• Simplified testing, can create a
dummy implementation that uses
fake data, make the frontend and
then swap to the actual class
in one place once it's done
• DRY - common code can go in
a service instead of being repeated
in many different places
Steps involved to get a response:
View is rendered
The view file is executed after the variables have
been loaded into scope. Partials are included
and HTML markup is generated to be sent to the user.
